messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

I can’t determine the endpoint path and the allowed HTTP methods from the three files you provided because the actual blueprint that implements the endpoint — the file_api blueprint — is created in app/api/cms/file.py (and the InfoCrud base may add/define routes), and that file (and/or the InfoCrud implementation) is not included.

What I can conclude from the provided files
- The CMS blueprint is registered at the URL prefix "/cms" (app/api/cms/__init__.py).
- The file-related blueprint is registered under that CMS blueprint at the URL prefix "/file" (app/api/cms/__init__.py).
- Therefore any route defined inside the file_api blueprint will be mounted under the prefix /cms/file. For example:
  - If file_api defines a route for "/" (route = "/"), the full path will be: /cms/file
  - If it defines a route for "/<int:id>", the full path will be: /cms/file/{id}
  - If it defines other route patterns, those will be appended to /cms/file accordingly.

What I still need to determine the precise path and allowed methods
- Contents of app/api/cms/file.py (this is where file_api is defined; I need to see the route decorator(s), registered URL rule(s), and the methods argument(s) provided there).
- If file_api’s routes are generated dynamically (for example by InfoCrud or other helper), I also need the implementation of InfoCrud (likely in app/lin or app/lin/*.py) to know which HTTP methods it exposes and how it names/structures routes (e.g., whether it uses /, /<id>, /<id>/something, etc.).

Please provide at least:
- app/api/cms/file.py
and, if file_api’s routes are created by InfoCrud or another helper:
- the file that defines InfoCrud (for example app/lin.py or the module under app/lin that defines InfoCrud)

Once I have those, I will output:
- the full HTTP request path(s) (with path parameters as {param})
- whether "all" methods are accepted (if the implementation uses an "all methods" handler)
- per-method acceptability for HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH
- a brief explanation of how each conclusion was reached.
